        "title": 		"How do cyber criminals target people's emotions?",
        "body": <<<"
			<p>Although you may be familiar with signs of a phishing email, not all phishing attempts are so obvious. Even when people know what to look out for, they are still falling for phishing attacks. Experts in the field are still falling for phishing attacks -usually because they get caught up in the moment and ignore their privacy plan, or their plan was incomplete.</p>

			<p>By learning how cybercriminals exploit your emotions, pressures and bad habits, you'll be able to protect against a greater variety of phishing techniques, even more sophisticated ones that aren't so obvious.</p>

			<p>The best solution is to stay calm and analytical, and develop good habits when interacting with anyone online, or trying to access your information or identity. Stay vigilant even when receiving emails or requests from internal sources or trusted contacts - they may have been compromised, as well. These strategies are also used in phone,SMS and social media scams, so recognising and taking action to mitigate these tactics will help protect yourself from across different forms of communication.</p>
		">>>,
